.TH "drm_syncobj_create" 9 "drm_syncobj_create" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
drm_syncobj_create \- create a new syncobj
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" drm_syncobj_create
.BI "(struct drm_syncobj **out_syncobj "  ","
.BI "uint32_t flags "  ","
.BI "struct dma_fence *fence "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "out_syncobj" 12
returned syncobj
.IP "flags" 12
DRM_SYNCOBJ_* flags
.IP "fence" 12
if non-NULL, the syncobj will represent this fence
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
This is the first function to create a sync object. After creating, drivers
probably want to make it available to userspace, either through
\fBdrm_syncobj_get_handle\fP or \fBdrm_syncobj_get_fd\fP.

Returns 0 on success or a negative error value on failure.
